WEBVTT

1
00:00:13.412 --> 00:00:15.629
This is me at age seven.
这是我七岁的时候，

2
00:00:17.659 --> 00:00:19.357
And this is also me.
这也是我。

3
00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:24.641
(Applause and cheering)
（掌声和欢呼）

4
00:00:24.665 --> 00:00:29.011
To be standing here in Kakuma refugee camp feels so surreal,
能够站在卡库马难民营做演讲， 感觉是那么的不真实，

5
00:00:29.035 --> 00:00:31.496
and I'm overcome with so much emotion.
我的内心不禁感慨良多。

6
00:00:32.075 --> 00:00:34.078
These very grounds are where I was born
我出生在卡库马这片土地，

7
00:00:34.102 --> 00:00:36.279
and spent the first seven years of my life.
也在这里度过了我人生的第一个七年，

8
00:00:37.698 --> 00:00:39.778
I think many people are surprised to hear
我想很多人听到

9
00:00:39.802 --> 00:00:42.331
that I had a great upbringing here at Kakuma.
我能在卡库马受到良好的教育 都很惊讶，

10
00:00:42.850 --> 00:00:44.579
But I was happy,
（在这片土地）我很开心，

11
00:00:44.343 --> 00:00:46.809
I was smart, I had friends
我很聪明，还交了许多朋友，

12
00:00:46.833 --> 00:00:49.728
and above all, I had hope for a brighter future.
最重要的是，我相信 我的未来是光明的。

13
00:00:50.662 --> 00:00:53.741
That's not to say that we didn't have our obstacles.
那不是说我们没有任何障碍了，

14
00:00:52.944 --> 00:00:55.526
I mean, boy were there struggles.
我的意思是， 生存在这儿本身就是困难的。

15
00:00:55.420 --> 00:00:57.910
I would sometimes get sick with malaria
有时候我会感染疟疾，

16
00:00:57.934 --> 00:01:01.392
and didn't always know where our next meal would come from.
而且总是吃了上顿不知道 还有没有下顿，

17
00:01:01.416 --> 00:01:04.842
But the sense of community that is here in Kakuma
但是在卡库玛， 大家对这个社区有着很强的归属感，

18
00:01:04.866 --> 00:01:07.311
and the pride that everyone here possesses
还为身为这个社区的一份子感到自豪，

19
00:01:07.335 --> 00:01:09.294
is simply unparalleled.
这些感情都是无可比拟的。

20
00:01:11.536 --> 00:01:14.591
When I was younger, I remember conflicts breaking out.
早些年的时候， 我记得冲突时常爆发，

21
00:01:14.975 --> 00:01:18.234
That tends to happen when people come from different backgrounds
主要是因为大家有着不同的背景，

22
00:01:18.258 --> 00:01:20.122
and don't speak the same language.
说着不同的语言。

23
00:01:20.146 --> 00:01:21.427
Eventually, Swahili --
最终，斯瓦希里——

24
00:01:21.451 --> 00:01:22.690
the main language here --
这里的主要语言——

25
00:01:22.714 --> 00:01:23.916
became our common ground.
成为了我们共同的根基。

26
00:01:24.687 --> 00:01:26.615
I made friends with the kids at the camp
我和难民营的孩子们成为了朋友，

27
00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:29.322
and even started embracing some of their cultures,
甚至开始接受他们中一些人的文化，

28
00:01:29.346 --> 00:01:32.992
celebrating holidays like Christmas even though I was raised Muslim.
比如庆祝像圣诞节一样的节日， 即便我生长在穆斯林的家庭，

29
00:01:33.592 --> 00:01:36.282
The other kids would embrace my culture as well,
其他的孩子们也同样会接受我的文化，

30
00:01:36.306 --> 00:01:38.731
sometimes even praying right alongside me.
有时候他们甚至会在我身旁一起做祷告。

31
00:01:39.763 --> 00:01:42.481
It was easy, as children, to come together,
孩子们总是很容易就打成一片，

32
00:01:42.505 --> 00:01:43.957
blend all of our beliefs
将我们的信仰融合在一起，

33
00:01:43.981 --> 00:01:47.436
to form our own unique, multicultural environment.
形成一个独一无二的多元文化环境。

34
00:01:49.078 --> 00:01:50.796
My name is Halima Aden
我的名字是哈利玛·亚登，

35
00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:54.500
and I'm a black, Muslim, Somali-American from Kenya.
我是一个黑人，信奉伊斯兰教， 我还是索马里裔的美国人，来自肯尼亚。

36
00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:58.808
(Applause)
（掌声）

37
00:01:58.832 --> 00:02:01.099
Some have called me a trailblazer --
有些人称我为先锋——

38
00:02:01.123 --> 00:02:04.142
I was the first Muslim homecoming queen at my high school,
我是我高中返校日舞会上 第一个获得皇后桂冠的穆斯林，

39
00:02:04.166 --> 00:02:06.929
the first Somali student senator at my college
我是我大学里第一个索马里裔的议员，

40
00:02:06.953 --> 00:02:09.760
and the first hijab-wearing woman in many places,
还是第一个在许多场合 带希贾布头巾的女性，

41
00:02:09.784 --> 00:02:12.755
like the Miss Minnesota USA beauty pageant,
如明尼苏达州举办的美国小姐选拔赛，

42
00:02:12.779 --> 00:02:15.838
the runways of Milan and New York Fashion Weeks
米兰和纽约时装周的舞台上，

43
00:02:15.862 --> 00:02:18.900
and even on the historic cover of British "Vogue."
甚至我还破天荒的登上了 英国《时尚》杂志的封面。

44
00:02:19.598 --> 00:02:20.748
As you can see,
正如大家所看到的，

45
00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:24.669
I'm not afraid to be the first, to step out on my own,
我不惧怕成为一名先锋， 踏出自己的舒服区，

46
00:02:24.693 --> 00:02:26.289
to take risks and seek change,
去冒险，去寻求改变，

47
00:02:26.313 --> 00:02:28.814
because that's what being a minority is about.
因为成为少数群体的意义所在，

48
00:02:28.838 --> 00:02:31.759
It's about using yourself as a vessel to create change
就是要将自己当成创造改变的媒体，

49
00:02:31.783 --> 00:02:36.296
and being a human representation for the power of diversity.
成为展现多元力量的人类大使，

50
00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:40.352
And now I use my platform to spread an important message of acceptance.
现在我在利用自己的平台， 传递包容开放的重要信息，

51
00:02:42.292 --> 00:02:43.912
But it hasn't always been easy.
但这并非易事。

52
00:02:44.546 --> 00:02:48.355
When we first arrived to the United States and made St. Louis, Missouri home,
在我初次抵达美国， 在圣路易斯密苏里州安家后，

53
00:02:49.284 --> 00:02:53.247
I remember asking my mom, "Is this really America?"
我记得我问我的母亲， “这真的是美国吗？”

54
00:02:54.014 --> 00:02:56.888
There were things that were sadly familiar,
因为有一些事让我觉得熟悉的悲哀，

55
00:02:56.912 --> 00:02:58.434
like hearing gunshots at night
像在半夜听到枪声，

56
00:02:58.458 --> 00:03:00.286
and the streets looking impoverished.
街道看起来那么的穷困，

57
00:03:01.148 --> 00:03:03.984
But there were things that were also very different.
但也有一些非常不同的地方。

58
00:03:04.008 --> 00:03:05.696
Like when I started first grade,
比如在我上一年级的时候，

59
00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:07.828
I noticed how the kids played in groups.
我注意到孩子们都是 分小团体玩耍的，

60
00:03:07.852 --> 00:03:09.978
In America, we call them "cliques."
在美国，我们称之为“小圈子”

61
00:03:10.002 --> 00:03:12.237
Back here, we all played together.
而在卡库玛，我们是大家一起玩的。

62
00:03:12.844 --> 00:03:14.415
Gender didn't matter,
性别无关紧要，

63
00:03:14.439 --> 00:03:16.584
and race most certainly never mattered.
种族更加不是问题。

64
00:03:17.066 --> 00:03:19.225
I remember asking myself,
我记得我问自己，

65
00:03:19.249 --> 00:03:21.161
"Why don't they understand Swahili?
为什么他们听不懂斯瓦希里语呢？

66
00:03:21.473 --> 00:03:24.412
Swahili is the language that brings people together."
斯瓦希里语可以让人团结在一起。

67
00:03:26.425 --> 00:03:27.607
To make matters worse,
更糟糕的是，

68
00:03:27.631 --> 00:03:31.333
the school I was enrolled in didn't have an English immersion program.
我上的那所学校不提供 全英文培训课程，

69
00:03:31.853 --> 00:03:34.045
So everyday I would get up,
虽然（和其他同学一样） 我每天起床，

70
00:03:34.069 --> 00:03:36.164
go to school, sit in my desk
上学，坐在课桌前，

71
00:03:36.188 --> 00:03:37.405
and never learn a thing.
但我却什么都没学到。

72
00:03:38.593 --> 00:03:40.590
This is when I started losing hope,
我开始失去希望，

73
00:03:40.614 --> 00:03:43.696
and I wanted nothing more than return to Kakuma,
一心只想回到卡库玛，

74
00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:44.876
a refugee camp.
一个难民营。

75
00:03:47.658 --> 00:03:50.567
Soon, my mother learned that many Somalis found refuge
很快，我母亲得知许多索马里人

76
00:03:49.857 --> 00:03:52.533
in a small town in Minnesota.
在明尼苏达州的一个小镇上 找到了一处容身之所，

77
00:03:52.933 --> 00:03:55.703
So when I was eight, we moved to Minnesota.
所以在我八岁的时候， 我们就搬去了明尼苏达州。

78
00:03:57.146 --> 00:04:01.260
My life changed as I met other students who spoke Somali,
我的生活在就此完全改变了， 我遇到了其他同样说索马里语的学生，

79
00:04:01.284 --> 00:04:04.539
attended a school that had an English immersion program
参加了全英文培训课程，

80
00:04:04.563 --> 00:04:07.302
and found teachers that would go above and beyond,
还遇到了一些不辞劳苦， 真心付出的老师，

81
00:04:07.326 --> 00:04:09.976
staying there after school hours and lunch breaks,
愿意在放学后或者午餐时间留下来，

82
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.126
dedicated to helping me find success in the classroom.
帮助我在学业上重新取得成功。

83
00:04:14.247 --> 00:04:19.152
Being a child refugee has taught me that one could be stripped of everything:
身为一个难民营的孩子， 我知道我们随时会失去一切：

84
00:04:19.176 --> 00:04:22.120
food, shelter, clean drinking water,
食物，住所，干净的饮用水，

85
00:04:22.144 --> 00:04:23.733
even friendship,
甚至友谊，

86
00:04:23.757 --> 00:04:26.836
but the one thing that no one could ever take away from you
唯有一样不会被夺走的东西

87
00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:28.191
is your education.
那就是教育。

88
00:04:28.598 --> 00:04:31.353
So I made studying my top priority
所以我把教育摆在了优先的位置，

89
00:04:31.377 --> 00:04:33.925
and soon started flourishing within the classroom.
很快我就在教室里崭露头角。

90
00:04:35.974 --> 00:04:39.201
As I grew older, I became more aware of others
随着年龄的增长， 我更懂得了人情世故，

91
00:04:39.225 --> 00:04:41.632
and how they viewed my race and background.
以及其他人如何看待我的种族和背景。

92
00:04:42.123 --> 00:04:45.490
Specifically, when I started wearing the head scarf known as a hijab.
尤其是，在我开始戴上头巾，即希贾布的时候。

93
00:04:46.485 --> 00:04:49.138
When I first started wearing it, I was excited.
第一次戴头巾的时候，我很兴奋，

94
00:04:49.162 --> 00:04:53.851
I remember admiring my mother's, and I wanted to emulate her beauty.
我记得我很喜欢我母亲的头巾， 我想像她戴上头巾时一样美丽，

95
00:04:53.875 --> 00:04:56.112
But when I started middle school,
但在我上中学时，

96
00:04:56.136 --> 00:04:58.912
the students teased me about not having hair,
我的同学们嘲笑我，说我没有头发，

97
00:04:58.936 --> 00:05:00.546
so to prove them wrong,
为了证明他们错了，

98
00:05:00.570 --> 00:05:03.013
I started showing them my hair --
我开始给他们展示我的头发，

99
00:05:03.037 --> 00:05:07.141
something that goes against my beliefs, but something I felt pressured to do.
虽然这与我的信仰相悖， 但却是我不得不做的，

100
00:05:07.763 --> 00:05:10.127
I wanted so badly to fit in at the time.
因为那个时候我太想融入他们的群体。

101
00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:17.479
When I reflect on the issues of race, religion, identity,
当我回想起关于种族，信仰和身份 这些问题时，

102
00:05:17.503 --> 00:05:19.809
a lot of painful memories come to mind.
许多痛苦的回忆涌上心头。

103
00:05:20.464 --> 00:05:23.754
It would be easy for me to blame those of another culture
也许指责那些因为不同文化背景

104
00:05:23.778 --> 00:05:26.504
for making me feel the pain I felt,
而给我带来痛苦的人会让我好受得多，

105
00:05:26.528 --> 00:05:27.941
but when I think deeper,
但想深一层，

106
00:05:27.965 --> 00:05:30.869
I also recognize that the most impactful,
我意识到曾经发生在我身上， 影响我最深，

107
00:05:30.893 --> 00:05:34.401
positive, life-changing events that have happened to me
最积极，彻底改变我命运的事件，

108
00:05:34.425 --> 00:05:37.044
are thanks to those people who are different than me.
都是多亏于那些与我不同的人。

109
00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:42.079
It was at this moment that I decided to step outside of my comfort zone
而正是那一刻， 我决定我要踏出我的舒服区，

110
00:05:42.103 --> 00:05:45.257
and compete in a pageant wearing a hijab and burkini.
戴上希贾布头巾和穿上博基尼泳衣 参加选美比赛。

111
00:05:46.242 --> 00:05:49.339
I saw it as an opportunity to be a voice for women
我将这个比赛看作一次 为女性发声的机会，

112
00:05:49.363 --> 00:05:51.895
who, like myself, had felt underrepresented.
尤其是像我自己这样的女性， 因为没有人为我们代言。

113
00:05:53.587 --> 00:05:55.644
And although I didn't capture the crown,
尽管我没有夺得桂冠，

114
00:05:55.668 --> 00:05:58.119
that experience opened so many doors for me.
但那段经历为我开启了许多大门。

115
00:05:58.772 --> 00:06:02.763
I was receiving emails and messages from women all over the world,
我收到了许多来自世界各地的女性 发给我的邮件和信息，

116
00:06:02.787 --> 00:06:06.978
telling me that I've inspired them by simply staying true to myself.
告诉我，是我坚持做自己的精神 激励了她们。

117
00:06:07.927 --> 00:06:09.873
The other "firsts" kept coming.
因此许许多多的“第一次”接踵而来，

118
00:06:10.583 --> 00:06:15.324
I was invited to New York City by fashion icon Carine Roitfeld
我受到了时尚偶像卡琳·洛菲德的 邀请前往纽约

119
00:06:15.348 --> 00:06:17.571
to shoot my very first editorial.
拍摄我的第一组时尚写真。

120
00:06:18.032 --> 00:06:21.596
It was around this time that I became the first hijab-wearing model,
而正是那时候， 我成为了第一个戴希贾布头巾的模特，

121
00:06:21.620 --> 00:06:23.164
and in my first year,
在（我工作的）第一年里，

122
00:06:23.188 --> 00:06:26.466
I graced the covers of nine fashion magazines.
我登上了九本时尚杂志的封面，

123
00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:29.787
It was a whirlwind, to say the least.
毫不夸张的说， 这一切就像一场旋风一样。

124
00:06:29.811 --> 00:06:32.180
But with all the overnight success,
但即使我一夜成名，

125
00:06:32.204 --> 00:06:35.124
there was one thing that remained constant --
有一点始终不变的是，

126
00:06:35.148 --> 00:06:38.935
the thought that this could be what brings me back here to Kakuma,
让我也许会重返这里， 重返卡库玛的想法，

127
00:06:38.959 --> 00:06:40.593
the place that I call home.
这片我称为家的土地。

128
00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:46.797
And just a few months ago, something incredible happened to me.
几个月之前，一件不可思议的事 发生在我身上了，

129
00:06:47.587 --> 00:06:50.230
I was in New York City, on a photo shoot,
当时我在纽约拍摄一组照片，

130
00:06:50.254 --> 00:06:53.303
when I met South Sudanese model Adut Akech,
就在那我遇到了一个来自南苏丹的 模特阿度特·艾凯奇（Adut Akech），

131
00:06:53.327 --> 00:06:56.448
who also happened to be born right here in Kakuma.
她恰巧也出生在这儿，卡库玛。

132
00:06:57.983 --> 00:07:01.710
That experience in itself is the definition of hope.
那段经历向我们诠释了什么叫希望，

133
00:07:02.219 --> 00:07:04.159
I mean, just imagine:
我的意思是，想象一下，

134
00:07:04.183 --> 00:07:07.825
two girls born in the same refugee camp,
两个来自同一个难民营的女孩，

135
00:07:07.849 --> 00:07:11.791
reunited for the first time on the cover of British "Vogue."
因为拍摄英国《时尚》杂志， 而首次团聚了。

136
00:07:12.377 --> 00:07:17.909
(Applause and cheering)
（掌声和欢呼）

137
00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:22.323
I was given the distinct pleasure of partnering up with UNICEF,
我受到了莫大的殊荣， 能够和联合国儿童基金会合作，

138
00:07:22.347 --> 00:07:25.970
knowing firsthand the work that they do for children in need.
直接了解到他们为需要帮助的儿童 所做的一切。

139
00:07:27.106 --> 00:07:28.766
And I want you to remember
我希望大家可以记住，

140
00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:31.796
that although the children here may be refugees,
卡库玛里的孩子也许是难民，

141
00:07:32.836 --> 00:07:34.733
they are children.
但他们依然是孩子。

142
00:07:34.906 --> 00:07:40.145
They deserve every opportunity to flourish, to hope, to dream --
他们同样应该享有发展， 抱有希望，拥有梦想——

143
00:07:40.934 --> 00:07:42.562
to be successful.
取得成功的机会。

144
00:07:44.342 --> 00:07:49.053
My story began right here in Kakuma refugee camp,
因为我的故事， 不就发生在卡库玛难民营里吗？

145
00:07:49.077 --> 00:07:50.831
a place of hope.
这片充满希望的土地。

146
00:07:51.321 --> 00:07:52.472
Thank you.
谢谢大家。

147
00:07:52.496 --> 00:07:57.081
(Applause)
（掌声）